## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)



A Pre-Analysis Plan (PAP) is a document that formalizes and declares the design and analysis plan for your study. It is written before the analysis is conducted and is generally registered on a third-party website.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)



The objectives of a PAP is to improve research design choices, increase research transparency, and allow other researchers to replicate your analysis.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)



A Pre-Analysis Plan (PAP) is a document that formalizes and declares the design and analysis plan for your study. It is written before the analysis is conducted and is generally registered on a third-party website.1

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?



(1) Start with a Study Design Overview  
  
(2) Follow with your Hypotheses  
  
(3) Specify your Measures and Index Construction: how you measure or operationalize variables of interest, including outcomes, covariates, and explanatory variables. These operationalizations can be included as its own section, or the operationalization of variables can be included after the hypothesis for which each variable is relevant.  
  
(4) Continue with an Estimation Procedure, this is your testing and estimation procedures. Clearly specify what you are estimating (i.e. the estimand) and how you intend to estimate it (i.e. the estimator).  
  
(5) Establish your Inference Criteria: decision rules for determining the detectability of effects  
  
(6) Establish Procedures for Data Issues: experiments and data collection often do not go the way that one expects or hopes.  
  
(7) Finally, include Power Analysis to calculate the likelihood that your study will detect an effect, if there is an effect to be detected.

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)



Having clarity of the design of the experiment, knowledge about statistical stimation procedures and analysis.

## Reflections: What to keep in mind when using the tool for R&amp;D purposes?



As a result, we recommend focusing the PAP on analytic details that will help you analyze your study and allow other researchers to replicate your analysis. A brief section on theory should be included insofar as it helps articulate hypotheses, but a detailed theory and literature review need not be included. The PAP does not need to include the front-end of an academic paper if these sections do not help you think about your analysis or help readers replicate your analysis.

## Credit: Who developed the tool or method?



Evidence in Governance and Politics (EGAP) is a research, evaluation, and learning network with worldwide reach that promotes rigorous knowledge accumulation, innovation, and evidence-based policy in various governance domains, including accountability, political participation, mitigation of societal conflict, and reducing inequality. It does so by fostering academic-practitioner collaborations, developing tools and methods for analytical rigor, and training academics and practitioners alike, with an intensive focus in the Global South.

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)

EGAP is a global research, evaluation and learning network that promotes rigorous knowledge accumulation, innovation, and evidence-based policy in various governance domains.  
  
EGAP promotes researcher-practitioner collaborations, develops tools and methods for analytical rigor, and trains researchers and practitioners alike, with an intensive focus in the Global South. EGAP members are designing and implementing field experiments throughout the world to address today’s most important questions in the fields of government and politics.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)

+ Helps find experimental designs and previous research that connects to the work we are doing.  
  
+ Provides a standard way of sharing experimentation designs and results.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)

Finding experimental designs already used in certain topics, to guide the design of new experiments or explore research associated with a problem or solution.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)
